08139nam a22011655i 9780674333505DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20131974mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013962411  a(OCoLC)1029812028  a(OCoLC)1032679838  a(OCoLC)1037978776  a(OCoLC)1042025377  a(OCoLC)1046611626  a(OCoLC)1047014932  a(OCoLC)1049619108  a(OCoLC)1054878404  a97806743335057 a10.4159/harvard.97806743335052doi  a(DE-B1597)248364  a(OCoLC)900840617  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aBV3415.2 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a266/.023/095104aThe Missionary Enterprise in China and America /ced. by John K. Fairbank.  aReprint 2013 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4c©1974  a1 online resource (442 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHarvard Studies in American-East Asian Relations ;v600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction: The Many Faces of Protestant Missions in China and the United States -- tPART I Protestant Missions in American Expansion -- tNear East Notes and Far East Queries -- tEvangelical Logistics: Mission Support and Resources to 1920 -- tThe Student Volunteer Movement and Its Role in China Missions, 1886-1920 -- tModernism and Missions: The Liberal Search for an Exportable Christianity, 1875—1935 -- tPART II Christianity and the Transformation of China -- tThe Theology of American Missionaries in China, 1900— 1950 -- tChristianity in the Chinese Idiom: Young J. Allen and the Early Chiao-hui hsin-pao, 1868—1870 -- tLittoral and Hinterland in Nineteenth Century China: The "Christian" Reformers -- tChristianity and Nationalism: The Career of Wu Lei-ch’uan at Yenching University -- tPART III China Mission Images and American Policies -- tEnds and Means: Missionary Justification of Force in Nineteenth Century China -- tWhy They Stayed: American Church Politics and Chinese Nationalism in the Twenties -- tThe Missionary Response to the Nationalist Revolution -- tThe Missionary Enterprise and Theories of Imperialism -- tNotes. Glossary. Index -- tNOTES -- tGLOSSARY -- tIndex -- tHARVARD STUDIES IN AMERICAN-EAST ASIAN RELATIONS -- tCONTRIBUTORS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor more than a century missionaries were the main contact points between the Chinese and American peoples. Often frustrated in saving Chinese souls, they nevertheless founded hospitals and colleges, and meanwhile on the American scene they helped form the image of China. This volume offers views of missionary roles in the United States and in China. Early American Protestant missions moved on from the Near East to the Far East. The second great surge of American missionary expansion in the 1880s was signaled by the formation of more business-like mission boards, by the Student Volunteer Movement to recruit liberal arts college graduates for evangelism abroad, and by the Layman's Movement to back them up. During the same period in China, missionary journalism was reaching a new Chinese-Christian community, and missionary educational and medical work was building modern institutions of social value for Chinese communities. A few "Christian reformers" emerged in China's treaty ports, and by the end of the century there was a missionary contribution to the reform movement in general. By the 1920s missionary and Chinese Christian educators were collaborating in Christian colleges like Yenching University, only to meet eventual disaster as the Nationalist revolution and Japan's invasion precipitated the great Chinese Communist-led revolution of the 1940s and after. American missions contributed fundamentally both to the revolutionary changes in China and to the American public response to them, although their impact on American policy s less clear. Fourteen contributors studying both sides of the missionary effort, in China and in America, present case studies that suggest conclusions and themes for research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aGeschichte. 0aMisiones americanas. 0aMission. 0aMissions, American. 0aTheologie, Christentum. 0aZending. 4aHISTORY / General. 4aMissions -- China. 4aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General. 4aProtestant churches -- Missions. 4aRELIGION / Christian Ministry / Missions. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBennett, Adrian A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCreighton Miller, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFairbank, John K.1 aFairbank, John K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFairbank, John K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aField, James A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchison, William R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiu, Kwang-Ching, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Clifton J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabe, Valentin H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchlesinger, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSearle Bates, M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStone Garrett, Shirley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVarg, Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWest, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backli